\begin_layout Standard
In the case of QE, we call this diversified expansion method MMR Query Expansion
 (MMRQE).
 MMRQE takes as input a PRF set, which is used to build a document-term
 matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 documents and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 terms as shown in Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Notation"

\end_inset

 (the TF-IDF is used to populate the matrix for each document vector).
 To represent the query 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 in the documents' dimension as in Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Notation"

\end_inset

, we use the BM25 or TF-IDF score between each document 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the query.
 Hence, given a query representation 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, MMRQE aims to select an optimal subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 terms 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}^{*}\subset D$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $|T_{k}^{*}|=k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ll|m|$
\end_inset

) relevant to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 but inherently different from each other (i.e., diverse).
 This can be achieved by building 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}^{*}$
\end_inset

 in a greedy manner by choosing the next optimal term 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k}^{*}$
\end_inset

 given the previous set of optimal term selections 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k-1}^{*}=\{t_{1}^{*},\ldots,t_{k-1}^{*}\}$
\end_inset

 (assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}^{*}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

) using the MMR diverse selection criterion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{k}^{*}=\argmax_{t_{k}\notin T_{k-1}^{*}}\hspace{-0.3mm}[\lambda\cos(Q,t_{k})-\hspace{-0.3mm}(1-\lambda)\max_{t_{j}\in T_{k-1}^{*}}\cos(t_{j},t_{k})]\label{eq:MMRQE-QR}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, the first cosine similarity term measures relevance between the query
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and possible expansion term 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k}$
\end_inset

 while the second term penalizes the possible expansion term according to
 its cosine similarity with any currently selected term in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k-1}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 trades off relevance and diversity.
 For MMRQE, we found that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0.5$
\end_inset

 generally provide the best results, according to our experiments on the
 CLEF-IP training dataset collection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For QR, we can greedily rebuild the query from scratch, while choosing diversifi
ed terms from the query itself.
 Here, we call this approach MMR Query Reduction (MMRQR).
 Formally, given a query representation 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, MMRQR aims to select an optimal subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 terms 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}^{*}\subset Q$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $|T_{k}^{*}|=k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k<|Q|$
\end_inset

) relevant to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 but inherently different from each other (i.e., diverse).
 This can be achieved by building 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}^{*}$
\end_inset

 in a greedy manner by choosing the next optimal term 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k}^{*}$
\end_inset

 given the previous set of optimal term selections 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k-1}^{*}=\{t_{1}^{*},\ldots,t_{k-1}^{*}\}$
\end_inset

 (assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}^{*}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

) using an adaptation of the MMR diverse selection criterion.
 Note that we use all the sections of the patent documents in the PRF set
 to built the document-term matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 documents and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 terms shown in Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Notation"

\end_inset

.
 For MMRQR, we found that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0.8$
\end_inset

 generally provide the best results in our experiments on the CLEF-IP dataset
 collection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key insight we want to highlight is that MMRQE does not select expansion
 terms independently as in practical usage of Rocchio, but rather it selects
 terms that have uncorrelated usage patterns across documents, thus hopefully
 encouraging diverse term selection that covers more documents for a fixed
 expansion budget 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and ideally, higher recall.
\end_layout

